        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Ancagalon</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Just a thing to point out. Every level past 50 gets you new spells, plus a few more HP, plus a reduction in the range you agro critters, plus a increased chance of your spells landing, plus a decreased chance of a critters spells landing on you, plus 2 more points in Channeling, plus 1 more mana per tick while medding, plus an increase in any of your scaling spells (ie Deflux will do a few more HP's each cast as you level), plus... well, I cannot think of anymore. </P><P>So, why spend 2 AA points in mental clarity when getting another level will yeild you the same result? Why spend 5 points to get 10STA which will get you 20HP when you can get a couple levels level and get 30HP? </P><P>In my mind, unless you are level 60 and have nothing better to do with your XP, leveling is definately the answer, except for skills that yield ablities we do not normally get. Running speed is interesting, it gives us something new. As our specialization skill for spell disciplines other then one is capped at 50, spell casting mastery is interesting as it gives us something we cannot do through leveling. </P><P>Just my ramblings, but I would urge everyone to weigh the advantages between getting a new level and getting a new skill. In almost all cases, a new level will give your character better tools (much more then just your spells) then a new skill will.</P><P>Cheers,<BR>Ancagalon the Black</P><P> </font></td>
